    id: "ph-sample-memo",
    title: "Claim Construction Memo",
    group: "3. 权利要求解释备忘录范文（Claim Construction Memo）",
    text: `#### Short Legal Memo: Claim Construction Under Phillips

##### Question Presented
Under Phillips v. AWH, how should a court determine the meaning of a disputed patent claim term?

##### Short Answer
A court should give the claim term its ordinary and customary meaning as understood by a person of ordinary skill in the art at the time of the invention, read in the context of the entire patent. The specification is usually the single best guide to the meaning of a disputed term, but the court must avoid importing limitations from preferred embodiments into the claims.

##### Analysis
Phillips starts from the bedrock principle that the claims define the invention. The words of a claim are generally given their ordinary and customary meaning. That meaning is not determined in the abstract. Rather, it is the meaning the term would have to a person of ordinary skill in the art after reading the patent as a whole.

The specification plays a central role. Claims must be read in view of the specification, of which they are a part. The Federal Circuit explained that the specification is always highly relevant to claim construction and is usually dispositive; it is the single best guide to the meaning of a disputed term.

At the same time, Phillips warns against a common error: importing limitations from the specification into the claims. A patent may describe a preferred embodiment, but the claims are not automatically limited to that embodiment unless the patentee clearly defines the term or disclaims broader claim scope.

Extrinsic evidence, such as dictionaries and expert testimony, may be useful, but it is less significant than the intrinsic record. Dictionaries should not be used to divorce claim terms from the context of the patent.

##### Application to "baffles"
The disputed term was "baffles." The district court limited the term to structures extending at an oblique or acute angle and forming part of an interlocking barrier. The Federal Circuit disagreed with that restrictive construction. It concluded that the claim language, other claims, and specification did not require every baffle to perform every function described in the patent.

##### Conclusion
Phillips teaches that claim construction is context-driven. The specification is central, but it is a guide to meaning, not a license to import every feature of the preferred embodiment into the claims.`
